# GetNextSegment — replacement for GetNextStrip in the cell-based
# coverage architecture (Path C, 2026-05-01). Instead of returning a
# pre-computed long strip from polygon edge to polygon edge, the
# server picks the next unmowed cell reachable from the robot's
# current pose, walks forward in the preferred direction until it
# hits an obstacle, dead cell, or boundary, and returns that short
# dynamic path. This way:
#
#   * a plant in the middle of a row no longer "kills" the whole
#     strip; the segment just stops at the plant, BT marks the
#     blocked cells, next call picks up after the obstacle
#   * the planner adapts to obstacles seen mid-mowing without
#     restarting the whole coverage plan
#   * "DEAD" cells (unreachable after N failed attempts) are
#     respected and excluded from future segment selection until
#     decay restores them
#
# The BT consumer is a state machine `GetNextSegment` →
# `FollowSegment` (with `is_long_transit` deciding whether to
# disengage the blade). `GetNextStrip.srv` remains for backward
# compatibility during the migration but new code should target
# this srv.

uint32 area_index
float64 robot_x
float64 robot_y
# robot_yaw_rad is the current heading; used to bias selection
# toward the row most aligned with the robot's facing so it can
# resume without an extra in-place rotation.
float64 robot_yaw_rad
# prefer_dir_yaw_rad is the global mowing-row direction for this
# area (computed once via compute_optimal_mow_angle on the polygon
# MBR). Cells are scanned along this axis; BT supplies it so the
# server can flip it for boustrophedon (alternate rows mow in the
# opposite direction).
float64 prefer_dir_yaw_rad
# When true the server alternates direction between adjacent rows
# (snake pattern). When false every row is mowed in the same
# direction (with a transit between rows). Default: true.
bool boustrophedon
# Maximum desired segment length in metres. The server will return
# a path no longer than this even when the row is unobstructed.
# Keeps each FollowSegment short enough that obstacle changes
# observed during the segment are picked up by the next call.
# 0 → server uses its configured default (~3.0 m).
float64 max_segment_length_m
---
bool success
# True once every reachable cell in the area is mowed. BT exits
# the inner loop and asks GetNextUnmowedArea for the next area.
bool coverage_complete
# Path from current robot pose to the end of the segment, in the
# `map` frame. Empty when success=false or coverage_complete=true.
# The first pose is the entry to the row (slightly offset from the
# robot pose along prefer_dir); the last pose is target_cell_pose.
nav_msgs/Path segment_path
# Final pose of the segment — equals segment_path.poses.back()
# when path is non-empty. Provided as a separate field so callers
# don't need to dereference Path internals.
geometry_msgs/PoseStamped target_cell_pose
# True when the segment requires a transit (>~0.5 m to reach the
# row entry, OR a turn beyond ~30° vs current heading). BT uses
# this to decide whether to gate the blade off+on for the segment;
# false → blade stays on for a continuous mowing flow between
# adjacent cells.
bool is_long_transit
# Segment-level coverage stats for the GUI / diagnostics, NOT used
# by the BT for control flow.
float32 coverage_percent
uint32 segments_remaining_estimate
uint32 dead_cells_count
# Free-form tag for the GUI: "interior" | "headland" | "transit"
# | "complete". Replaces the GetNextStrip "phase" field.
string phase
# Why the segment ended at target_cell. One of:
#   "boundary"   — hit the area polygon edge
#   "obstacle"   — next cell is OBSTACLE_PERMANENT / OBSTACLE_TEMPORARY / NO_GO_ZONE
#   "dead_zone"  — next cell is LAWN_DEAD
#   "max_length" — segment hit max_segment_length_m
#   "row_end"    — boustrophedon turn at end of row
# BT can use this to decide whether to skip-cell-mark on next
# failure (e.g. "obstacle" → already known, don't double-count).
string termination_reason
